    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. i'll try to get a test kit. i'm just worried that something is actively draining the nutrients out of the soil before the plants can even get any. is it possible for the soil to just lose them really fast? like something is stealing them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it is absolutely possible for nutrients to be lost quickly, which is often called leaching. This happens when heavy watering washes soluble nutrients right past the plant's roots, especially in sandy soil. You can mitigate this by watering deeply but less frequently, encouraging the roots to grow deeper into the soil where nutrients are more stable. Also, incorporating organic matter, like compost, helps hold onto nutrients like a sponge, preventing them from washing away.",
      "source": "target",
